review_text: These exams are just ok. They cover a wide variety of topics, but explanations are highly inconsistent in quality. A few questions have answer choices that don't match the question, while others make unstated assumptions that effectively determine the correct answer. These exams also test rote memorization more than most others at the expense of testing conceptual knowledge. There are more questions here about specific Sagemaker settings and exact details of file formats than in any other practice exams I have tried.
Passed on 7/2025. This practice exam is great. The difficulty is align with actual exam. It will be better if add more questions.
Some of the questions that required looking at a graph were missing images. Other than that, test was great. The insights given after answering were great!

I passed the exam on 5/22/2025 and thought the questions in Frank's question set were slightly easier than the actual certification exam. In my book, that's ok because IMHO if I can't pass an easier exam, I'm not going to pass the actual thing.

While the video course is very professional and informative for the preparation for the exam, I find this practice exam contains quite a number of errors. For example I experienced 3 questions in the first 20 questions in the full test that require me to select answer based on specific details, but those details like "require of x condition" or "response within x seconds" are important when selecting the answer, and used in the answer explanation, but they are actually not in the question itself. Which I believe is human error when preparing the questions. Please review the question set, remove legacy elements and review the question set as this is not up to the overall standard of your courses
Even though there are some outdated selections (e.g. DeepLens, DeepRacer), it is still valuable for preparing for the certification

This practice test provides a reasonable representation of the actual exam. It could be perceived as too straightforward and closely aligned with the lessons provided by Sundog Education. Other practice exams, such as those from Singh, may offer a greater level of difficulty and provide a more diverse testing experience. Additionally, the explanations offered may be brief in nature. If you have relied primarily on the Sundog video lessons to prepare for the AWS machine learning exam, I would suggest also incorporating other practice exams into your study plan.

I passed the exam yesterday in one shot.

The makers of this content benefit greatly from the overall lack of AWS ML Specialty exam prep materials out there -- if they actually had to compete they'd sell nothing. Compared to the handful of other sources out there, the thoroughness of explanations for the Singh practice tests on this site and the Frlez content available in the Amazon Kindle marketplace, these hold up very poorly. These do beat Dr. Ahmed's materials though, which are disgustingly riddled with typos and offer zero explanation for practice test solutions
Negatives:

Questions are really good and explanation are clear. However, Question 55 seems to be ambiguous as it mentions simplest and storage efficient. When compared to the official practice exam, this exam is a more accurate representation of the actual exam. I passed the exam yesterday (June 30th). It is challenging, for a moment I started doubting if I would pass. When I was taking this practice exam I would finish with plenty of time to spare, not the actual exam I almost used all of the time. Time management is key, do not get stuck on trying to answer a question, flag it and move on. I was doing well on the first half of the exam, in my calculations I was going to have an hour to review the flagged questions, I did not. I had enough time to review the questions but barely. Depending on your experience this may not be the case for you. I took the official practice exam(I passed) a few days before the actual exam. I used the result to review areas with the lowest scores.

Passed the with a score of 955/1000 which translates to approximately 4 wrong questions out of 65. A lot of the credit goes to Frank for creating such a wonderful test set. The only difference is that in the actual exam the answers are even more close and confusing, in the sense that around 30% questions were too close to call and I had to use every iota of my memory , logic and general ML experience to finalize the answer. But this is only a minor issue since so far this is the best question set I have found on internet - way better than linuxacademy , acloudguru and AWS Official Practice exam( yes I took their tests as well). All in all very good place to test yourself once you have mastered the ML skills through various other courses , hands-on and AWS docs.
